## 2. What is the Market Pricing?

### Before the Iran war:
- March 19 rate cut was priced at approximately **80% probability**
- Market expected further cuts through 2026

### After the Iran war (as of 9-10 March 2026):
- March 19 cut now priced at **99% probability of a hold** — cut almost entirely priced out
- Markets indicate no rate cuts for the rest of 2026
- UK two-year gilt yields rose to 4.129%, up from 3.52% pre-war — on course for the biggest one-day increase since the Liz Truss mini-budget in 2022

*Source: The Guardian, 9 March 2026*

### Sell-side views:
**JPMorgan — Allan Monks (Chief UK Economist):**
> "BoE cuts are possible in the first half of 2026, but March is off the table and April requires a clear calming of geopolitical tensions. The Bank now faces another wave of inflation barring a significant and rapid de-escalation in the Middle East."

**UBS — Anna Titareva (European Economist):**
> "The meeting on March 19 is likely to be overshadowed by heightened uncertainty around the trajectory of energy prices. By the time of the March meeting, the MPC will not be able to determine the nature of the shock with sufficient certainty."
- UBS now forecasts next cuts in April and July (previously March and June)
- Only two of nine MPC members now likely to vote for a cut

*Source: CNBC, 9-10 March 2026; The Guardian, 9 March 2026*

### Critical data gap:
- **February CPI** will not be released until **25 March** — six days *after* the MPC decision
- The MPC will make its March 19 decision without any inflation data reflecting the Iran energy shock
- The first CPI print to meaningfully capture the full impact will likely be **March CPI** (mid-April) or **April CPI** (mid-May)
- **Next MPC meeting after March 19: 7 May 2026** — the first meeting with sufficient data

